---
/**
 * Case 1: Coastal Bangladesh — src/pages/case-bangladesh.astro
 *
 * Per docs/CONTENT-INVENTORY.md § Case 1. Seven content sections.
 */
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Link from "../components/Link.astro";
import Button from "../components/Button.astro";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import CitationBlock from "../components/CitationBlock.astro";
import BangladeshMap from "../components/BangladeshMap.astro";
import TimelineList from "../components/TimelineList.astro";

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ResearchProject",
  name: "3MIP Case 1: Coastal Bangladesh",
  description:
    "3MIP's first benchmark case asks participating teams to project net internal migration in coastal Bangladesh districts from 2025 to 2050 using a curated input dataset.",
  location: { "@type": "Place", name: "Coastal Bangladesh" },
  parentOrganization: { "@type": "Organization", name: "3MIP", alternateName: "Mobility and Migration Modeling Intercomparison Project" },
};

const timelineItems = [
  {
    date: "2025-10",
    dateLabel: "Now – mid 2026",
    text: "Teams run their models, attend webinars, share preliminary findings.",
    kind: "active" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "2026-07",
    dateLabel: "July 2026",
    text: "First synthesis presented at iEMSs Dublin (Session C7 + Workshop WSC7).",
    kind: "active" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "2026-12",
    dateLabel: "Late 2026 onward",
    text: "Submissions to <em>Climatic Change</em> topical collection. [VERIFY: formal Springer call not yet posted as of May 2026]",
    kind: "planned" as const,
  },
  {
    date: "2027",
    dateLabel: "2027",
    text: "Synthesis paper drafted from the collected outputs.",
    kind: "aspirational" as const,
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Case 1: Coastal Bangladesh"
  description="Coastal Bangladesh is 3MIP's first benchmark case. 175.7M people, sea-level rise, salinity, flood dynamics. Open dataset, shared protocol."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="page">
    <header class="page__header">
      <h1>Case 1: Coastal Bangladesh</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Bangladesh's coastal districts face one of the most studied combinations
        of climate stress and population pressure in the world. 3MIP's first
        benchmark case asks participating modeling teams to project net
        internal migration in these districts from 2025 to 2050 under shared
        climate and socioeconomic scenarios, using shared input data.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section aria-labelledby="why-h">
      <h2 id="why-h">Why Bangladesh is the first case</h2>
      <p>
        Three factors converge on Bangladesh. The empirical literature on
        internal migration there is among the densest in the climate-migration
        field, providing a real benchmark against which model outputs can be
        sanity-checked. The country's population of 175.7 million (UNFPA SWOP
        2025) and its low-lying delta geography make the policy stakes
        consequential. And the data infrastructure — population grids, modeled
        migration flows, salinity layers, flood histories — is already openly
        licensed and usable.
      </p>
      <p>
        Bell et al. (2021) projected that migration <em>toward</em> Bangladesh's
        coast, not away from it, will continue through 2100 across the
        sea-level rise scenarios they studied. That finding sits in productive
        tension with the popular narrative of mass climate exodus and provides
        the empirical motivation for revisiting the problem with multiple
        model architectures.
      </p>

      <CitationBlock
        authors="Bell, A. R., Wrathall, D. J., Mueller, V., Chen, J., Oppenheimer, M., et al."
        year={2021}
        title="Migration towards Bangladesh coastlines projected to increase with sea-level rise through 2100"
        venue="Environmental Research Letters"
        reference="16(2), 024045"
        doi="10.1088/1748-9326/abdc5b"
      />
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="q-h">
      <h2 id="q-h">The shared question</h2>
      <Callout variant="note" label="The shared question">
        <strong>Net internal migration in coastal Bangladesh districts, 2025–2050,
        under SSP2-4.5.</strong>
        Each participating team applies their model to this question using the
        curated input dataset. Teams may extend the analysis to SSP1-2.6 and
        SSP5-8.5 as sensitivity scenarios, and to 2100 as a sensitivity time
        horizon. <span class="verify">[VERIFY scenario specification with Bell — current FACTS.md draft]</span>
      </Callout>
      <p>
        Teams choose how to operationalize "migration" within their own model
        architecture. The intercomparison does not require harmonized output
        variables; it requires harmonized inputs and a shared central question.
        Where outputs diverge — and they will — the synthesis paper documents
        the divergence and the methodological choices that drive it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="geo-h">
      <h2 id="geo-h">Geographic scope</h2>
      <div class="geo">
        <div>
          <p>
            The case focuses on districts in the Ganges-Brahmaputra-Meghna
            delta and adjacent coastal areas. The exact district list is
            specified in the protocol document and includes Khulna, Satkhira,
            Bagerhat, Barguna, Patuakhali, Pirojpur, Bhola, Noakhali,
            Chattogram, and adjacent inland districts that receive coastal
            migrants <span class="verify">[VERIFY exact district list against protocol]</span>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <BangladeshMap />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="data-h">
      <h2 id="data-h">Curated input dataset</h2>
      <p>
        3MIP provides a harmonized, openly licensed dataset combining
        population grids, modeled migration flows, soil salinity, flood
        extent, and socioeconomic indicators. Teams use this dataset as their
        common input. They may add additional data sources if their model
        requires them, with documentation.
      </p>
      <p>
        <Link href="/data/" variant="in-prose">See the full data documentation</Link>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="time-h">
      <h2 id="time-h">Expected outputs and timeline</h2>
      <TimelineList items={timelineItems} />
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="proto-h">
      <h2 id="proto-h">Protocol document</h2>
      <p>
        The 3MIP Bangladesh case protocol document specifies the shared
        question, the curated dataset, the climate scenarios, the geographic
        scope, and the output submission process. Registered participants
        receive the latest version of the protocol.
      </p>
      <p>
        <Button href="/participate/">Request the protocol document</Button>
      </p>
      <p class="pending-note">
        <span class="pending">[PENDING BELL APPROVAL]</span> whether the protocol
        document is fully public or registration-gated. Default: registration-gated.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 48rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-7) var(--space-3) var(--space-8);
  }
  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .page { padding: var(--space-8) var(--space-5); }
  }
  .page__header { margin-bottom: var(--space-7); }
  .page__header h1 { margin: 0; }
  .lede {
    font-size: var(--text-body-lg);
    line-height: var(--text-body-lg--line-height);
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .page section { margin-top: var(--space-7); }
  .page h2 { margin: 0 0 var(--space-3); }
  .page p { margin: 0 0 var(--space-3); max-width: 65ch; }
  .page p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  .geo {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    align-items: start;
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
  }
  @media (min-width: 768px) {
    .geo {
      grid-template-columns: 3fr 2fr;
      gap: var(--space-5);
    }
  }
  .geo p { margin: 0; }

  .verify {
    color: var(--color-warning);
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .pending {
    color: var(--color-warning);
    font-size: var(--text-caption);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .pending-note {
    font-size: var(--text-small);
    color: var(--color-ink-muted);
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
  }
</style>
